ACT 1-1, Scnm: III.

Pamphilus, now left alone with Davus, and convinced by what he had heard that Chremes had no thought of giving him his daughter, is at a loss to conceive what his father could mean by such a pretence. Davus, whose character is that of a shrewd, cunning, penetrating slave, easily conjectures the true reason, and advises Pamphilus to pretend to his father that he is willing to marry, from which counsel new troubles arise.

Of this scene the first nine verses are Tetrarneter Trochaics Catalec- tic3 verses 10 to 19 inclusive, Trimeter Iambics; and the remainder, Tetrameter Iambics Acatalectic.
